<br>
Let me disassemble the arguments against it. <br>
Cendan says<br>
Its racism plain and simple. The pledge of allegiance represents all Americans. No where does it exclude anyone, what do you think the words &quot;one nation&quot; and &quot;indivisable&quot; mean?<br>
It excluded a lot of different religions when &quot;under God&quot; was added. The teachers stress that it is not used to advocate seperatism.<br>
<br>
Kytherion says<br>
But in my opinion if the Black Liberation Front (or whatever) wants to do this, then they can build their own damn schools and salute whatever they want. If the students find the ideals of seperatism uplifting, then the students can use their own money to preach it.<br>
It was the students who discovered it while researching kwanza. If they want to explore there past and honor those who fought for the rights they enjoy I applaud them. We teach them to honor Jefferson and Washington, do you know what they did for blacks? <br>
<br>
Gladetree says<br>
replace the word &quot;black&quot; with the word &quot;white&quot; and then just imagine how long this shit would last<br>
<br>
Replace the word black with the word Native American and less people would be complaining. We afford two standards in this country. We are eternally apologetic to the point of idiocy with Native Americans, but we still deny racism against blacks occurs to this very day. This was written by a group who fought for rights the rest of us have taken for granted. I admire the children for actually coming up with something positive from there past when all pop culture wants to show them is that blacks were slaves at one time and are pimpin' da hoes now. <br>
<br>
Poppen says<br>
Hmm..ok in a nutshell its sad..its a disgrace..and it's rediculous. This kind of action is fundamentally no different from a group of hooded white thugs walking down main street screaming white power. Sick...devisive, and smacking of a hollow struggle that no longer has a central driving force. Two hundered years ago..this would have been appropriate..but today..its a waste of time for these young black AMERICANS who should be busy bettering themselves with education rather than learning new ways to falsify a dead oppresion<br>
<br>
Two hundred years ago they would have been naked on an auction block. This is NOT ancient history. This kind of action is different. The white thugs motives are to keep the blacks down the blacks motives are to empower their youth. I look at the fact that it was brought to prominence in the school by the children as a point that they are bettering themselves. In fact I applaud the efforts of anybody able to expand history beyond the text book without changing it. <br>
<br>
Cendan further says<br>
Blacks don't deserve special treatment based on the suffering of their lineage.If you think that then should we still blame Germans for Hitler? Should Jews get special treatment too?<br>
I don't care if you are green, blue, black, red, or white. You live in America and you are American. Otherwise, move along, hope you enjoyed your visit.<br>
<br>
Do I deserve special treatment. I am part Irish and we celebrated St. Pat's day at my school. We did this because the Irish have strong roots here and it is a small community. Nobody was offended. Do you think if somebody from Britain, seeing a school with an Irish flag in the halls, who had suffered at the hands of the IRA would feel anger. Maybe, but he can fuck off. We celebrated the strengths of our culture. That was in our elementary school. I didn't even know about the IRA till several years later. A nearby town with an even smaller population has had a large influx of jews, russians and mexicans and already had strong backgrounds in Chzeckoslowhatever (can't ever remember that spelling you know where I am talking about) as well as a few other European countries. They have multicultural festivals during the summer. If we had multicultural festivals at my school it would still be Irish, this is a black school in the above example.<br>
As for giving the jews special treatment, i had an enlightening visit to the Holocaust Museum and hope I can take my kids someday to the only planned, but objected to for the same arguments as above, Underground Railroad Museum. <br>
<br>
Tell the children that what they have dug up on their ancestors past is blasphemy and evil and see how much more research they will be willing to do in the future. We are the ones taking it out of context. We view it as offensive, but read again how the children and teachers view it. Jesus fucking Christ in a country where education has become a dilemma and school violence is a national problem can we please let the children see something uplifting as just that and not be the ones to make it into an issue. In fact it says they say the pledge of allegiance as you and I know it standard anyway. <br>
<br>
You can tell them that we are one united country all you want nonetheless chances are they are going to be called nigger at some point. That is America. You can say you will never say that, but you cannot guarantee that the next person will not. In my opinion I would rather them gain racial identity through the people who helped shape their past then through some of the ways popular culture presents blacks as today. As much as I disagree with some of the teachings of Malcolm X, I would rather see a black youth reading Alex Haleys bio of him, then getting their lessons on how to deal with racial divisions from gangsta rap. <br>
<br>
Ritt <br>
<br>
