Kanibaal raises a very good point. The people who have been oppressed by racism simply because they are black are alive today and remember the hatred many white people showed them.<br>
<br>
A wider issue is that the US Federal Government had done little to stop racism and in particular the South. In general, I can see the perspectives of some that want the US Federal Government to compensate them for the extreme hardships they underwent.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, when will this cease? Does financial compensation really reverse the sins of the past? For that matter, doesn't having a &quot;Black pledge of allegiance&quot; simply reinstate segregation... a &quot;reverse segregation&quot;?<br>
<br>
I believe that all US Citizens should be concerned when the fundamentals of the country are tampered with openly. The Pledge of Allegiance is one of those fundamentals. <br>
<br>
The Pledge of Allegiance has already been used to divide the US. In 1892 when the pledge was first formulated it simply read &quot;I pledge allegiance to my Flag and the Republic for which it stands, one nation, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all.&quot; In 1954, after the Knights of Columbus lobbied heavily in congress, the pledge was changed with the addition of &quot;under God&quot;. The change was a blatant message in response to the so-called &quot;Red Scare&quot; that the US was not an atheistic communist country. However, the change also continues to be used to erode the fundamental pursuit of liberty in the US. Many athiests, such as my self, and other non-christians have been attacked for our beliefs by Christians who like to claim that the US is a &quot;Christian&quot; nation. Usually they pull out a dollar bill and point at the Pledge of Allegiance as evidence (when in fact it is not).<br>
<br>
It is best not to tamper with the Pledge of Allegiance. Sure, if some black private schools want an additional pledge to their race, then have at it. However, there is a large difference between a pledge to country and a pledge to race. One is a pledge of loyalty to all countrymen/countrywomen; the other is a racist pledge. When whites utter such a pledge (like the KKK and Neo-Nazis) they are at once denounced as scum sucking garbage. <p>Lurikeen Mali'Kyre<BR>
Necromancer <BR>
<BR>
"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"<br>
